 &nbsp; 

 This paper explores the use of the Frayer Model as an instructional strategy for developing geometric concepts among ninth-grade students in the Galilee region. The study employed a quantitative and qualitative approach to examine how the Frayer Model enhances students&rsquo; understanding of geometry through structured conceptual analysis, including definitions, examples, non-examples, and key characteristics. Findings indicate that this method significantly improved students&rsquo; conceptual clarity and engagement with mathematical content. The implications for geometry instruction and conceptual teaching in diverse educational contexts are discussed.

